SQL ORDER BY Keyword

The SQL ORDER BY keyword is used to sort the result-set in ascending or descending order.
By default, ORDER BY sorts results in ascending order (ASC).

ORDER BY Syntax:
SELECT column1, column2, ...
FROM table_name
ORDER BY column1, column2, ... ASC|DESC;

Example 1: Sort by Price Ascending
Sort the products from lowest to highest price:
SELECT * FROM Products
ORDER BY Price;

What this does:
This query returns all rows sorted by Price from lowest to highest.
When to use it:
Use this to rank results by numeric values in ascending order.

Example 2: Sort by Price Descending
Sort the products from highest to lowest price:
SELECT * FROM Products
ORDER BY Price DESC;

What this does:
This query returns all rows sorted by Price from highest to lowest.
When to use it:
Use this when you want the largest values first.

Example 3: Sort Alphabetically by ProductName
For text values, ORDER BY sorts alphabetically by default:
SELECT * FROM Products
ORDER BY ProductName;

What this does:
This query sorts product rows alphabetically by ProductName.
When to use it:
Use this for ordered lists of text values.

Example 4: Sort Alphabetically in Descending Order
Sort product names in reverse alphabetical order:
SELECT * FROM Products
ORDER BY ProductName DESC;

What this does:
This query sorts product names from Z to A.
When to use it:
Use this when you want reverse alphabetical output.

ORDER BY Several Columns
You can sort by more than one column. The result is first sorted by the first column, and
then by the second column when values in the first column are equal.

Example 5: Sort Customers by Country then CustomerName
SELECT * FROM Customers
ORDER BY Country, CustomerName;

What this does:
This query groups customers by Country, then sorts each group by CustomerName.
When to use it:
Use this when you need a hierarchical sort order.

Example 6: Combine ASC and DESC
Sort customers by Country ascending and then CustomerName descending:
SELECT * FROM Customers
ORDER BY Country ASC, CustomerName DESC;

What this does:
This query sorts countries A to Z and sorts names within each country Z to A.
When to use it:
Use this when you need different directions for different columns.

Example 7: Sort by Multiple Columns with Different Directions
Sort by Country ascending and CustomerID descending:
SELECT CustomerID, CustomerName, Country
FROM Customers
ORDER BY Country ASC, CustomerID DESC;

What this does:
This query sorts by Country and then shows higher CustomerIDs first within each country.
When to use it:
Use this when you want one column sorted ascending and another descending.

Example 8: Sort Numeric and Text Columns
Select customer name and postal code sorted by PostalCode ascending, then by CustomerName:
SELECT CustomerName, City, PostalCode
FROM Customers
ORDER BY PostalCode ASC, CustomerName;

What this does:
This query sorts rows by postal code, then sorts by name where postal codes match.
When to use it:
Use this when you want a primary and secondary sort key.

Example 9: Sort with WHERE and ORDER BY
Select Mexican customers ordered by City:
SELECT CustomerName, City, Country
FROM Customers
WHERE Country = 'Mexico'
ORDER BY City;

What this does:
This query first filters to Mexico and then sorts the results by city.
When to use it:
Use this when you need filtered and sorted output.

Example 10: Sort and Limit Results
Return the first 3 products by lowest price:
SELECT ProductID, ProductName, Price
FROM Products
ORDER BY Price
LIMIT 3;

What this does:
This query sorts by price and returns only the top three lowest-priced products.
When to use it:
Use this when you want a small ranked sample of results.

